Two‑Way Four‑Lane Road Design (Tilemap)

Goal
- Convert the current one‑way, 3‑lane tile system into a two‑way, 4‑lane system:
  - Two lanes per direction (A→B and B→A)
  - A physical divider/collision barrier between opposing directions within a tile
  - No divider or lane markings on junction tiles (isTurn=true)
  - Round‑robin turning at junctions
  - Multiple spawn points with a minimum threshold check before Driving mode
  - Dedicated spawn tiles
  - Add traffic signals at T/cross intersections for safe conflict resolution

Core Concepts
1) Tile types
   - Normal segment tile (4 lanes): two lanes each direction, with a central divider (collision‑active)
   - Junction tile (isTurn=true): no divider or lane dashes; acts as connector
   - Spawn tile: a designated endpoint tile (per direction) for safe car injection

2) Lanes and divider
   - Each segment tile provides two unidirectional lanes for Direction A and two for Direction B
   - A divider is drawn and collision‑active to prevent crossing into opposing direction
   - Lane dashes drawn only on normal tiles; omitted on junction tiles

3) Direction and routing
   - Cars are assigned a travel direction and lane at spawn
   - Movement is lane‑constrained; no use of opposing lanes by default
   - At junctions, use round‑robin selection for outgoing branches (per junction) to distribute flow

4) Spawn points and minimum threshold
   - Multiple spawn tiles allowed; each belongs to a direction and is an endpoint
   - Before entering Driving mode, compute minSpawnPoints by:
     - Heuristic (pick max of):
       - f1(area of outer bounding rectangle), or
       - f2(number of tiles), or
       - f3(number of junctions/branches)
   - If available spawn points < minSpawnPoints, alert user and keep Editing mode

5) Traffic signals at intersections
   - For T and cross intersections, attach a simple signal controller to the junction tile
   - Signal phases arbitrate conflicting movements to prevent collisions and reduce gridlock

6) Collision and visibility
   - Divider is part of collision geometry on segment tiles
   - On junction tiles, hide divider/dashes and rely on signals/priority

7) Extensibility
   - Later: add overtaking using adjacent lane when safe; add adaptive signal timing; add density‑aware spawn balancing

Out‑of‑Scope (initial phase)
   - Complex right‑of‑way rules beyond signals
   - Overtaking into opposing lanes
   - Multi‑vehicle platooning, advanced gap acceptance

Acceptance Criteria
   - Four lanes per segment tile with a collision divider
   - Junction tiles suppress dashes/divider
   - Round‑robin turning works at each junction
   - Multiple spawn tiles supported; min spawn threshold gated before Driving
   - Cars per direction stay in their lanes; no head‑on conflicts on the same lane segment
   - Signals control conflicts at T/cross junctions


